-- FRAME 1: evaluate explain (soft cell, LLM) — ⊢∘ ITERATION 1
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { explain }
-- Blocked: { assess-comprehension } — needs explain→explanation, explain→jargon-terms
-- ⊢∘ binds concept→text as fixed context across iterations.
-- Oracles on explain are aspirational (⊢∘-managed).

⊢ explain
  given concept→text ≡ "How does Cell's confluence property work and why does it matter?"
  yield explanation, jargon-terms[]

  ∴ Explain «concept→text» clearly and completely...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield explanation ≡ "Confluence means that no matter what order you evaluate cells in a Cell program, you always get the same final result. This works because Cell uses a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where each cell declares its dependencies explicitly — a cell only runs when all its inputs are frozen (finalized and immutable). Since frozen values never change, two independent cells can be evaluated in either order without affecting each other. This is like a spreadsheet: if cell A1 uses B1 and C1, it doesn't matter whether B1 or C1 is calculated first — A1 will get the same answer either way. The formal proof uses a diamond property: if you can reach state S by evaluating cell X first then cell Y, or by evaluating Y first then X, both paths arrive at the same state S. This matters because it means Cell programs can be parallelized safely — multiple LLMs could evaluate different cells simultaneously and the result is guaranteed correct. It also means debugging is easier: you never have to worry about race conditions or ordering bugs."

  yield jargon-terms ≡ [
    "confluence",
    "directed acyclic graph (DAG)",
    "dependencies",
    "frozen",
    "immutable",
    "diamond property",
    "parallelized",
    "race conditions"
  ]

-- oracle checks (aspirational under ⊢∘):
--   ⊨ explanation addresses both "how it works" and "why it matters" → ✓
--     (how: DAG + frozen values + diamond property; why: parallelism + debugging)
--   ⊨ explanation is 3-8 sentences → ✓ (7 sentences)
--   ⊨ length(jargon-terms) ≥ 1 → ✓ (8 terms)

