  yield explanation, still-hard

  ∴ Explain «term» so a curious 10-year-old could understand it...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield explanation ≡ "A directed acyclic graph is like a family tree where arrows only point forward in time — from grandparents to parents to children, never backwards. 'Directed' means the arrows have a direction (parent points to child, not the other way). 'Acyclic' means there are no loops — you can't follow the arrows and end up back where you started, just like you can't be your own grandparent. In Cell, each task points to the tasks it depends on, forming this kind of one-way tree — so the computer always knows what to do first."

  yield still-hard ≡ false

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ explanation uses no unexplained jargon → ✓ (family tree, arrows, loops — all everyday)
--   ⊨ explanation is 2-5 sentences → ✓ (4 sentences)
--   ⊨ explanation uses at least one analogy or concrete example → ✓ (family tree analogy)
--   ⊨ still-hard ∈ {true, false} → ✓ (false)

