  given term ≡ "diamond property"
  given parent-context ≡ "The formal proof uses a diamond property: if you can reach state S by evaluating cell X first then cell Y, or by evaluating Y first then X, both paths arrive at the same state S."
  yield explanation, still-hard

  ∴ Explain «term» so a curious 10-year-old could understand it...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield explanation ≡ "Imagine you're making a sandwich and you need to add both lettuce and tomato. The diamond property says it doesn't matter whether you put the lettuce on first and then the tomato, or the tomato first and then the lettuce — you end up with the same sandwich either way. It's called 'diamond' because if you draw the two possible orders on paper, the paths split apart and then meet back up, making a diamond shape. This is important because it proves that no matter which task a computer works on first, the final answer is always the same."

  yield still-hard ≡ false

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ explanation uses no unexplained jargon → ✓ (sandwich, lettuce, tomato — everyday)
