  ]
  given explainer-*→still-hard ≡ [false, false, false]
  yield full-explanation, remaining-hard[], leaf-score

  ∴ Assemble a complete explanation combining main explanation and sub-explanations...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield full-explanation ≡ "Confluence means that no matter what order you evaluate cells in a Cell program, you always get the same final result. This works because Cell uses a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where each cell declares its dependencies explicitly — a cell only runs when all its inputs are frozen (finalized and immutable). Since frozen values never change, two independent cells can be evaluated in either order without affecting each other. This is like a spreadsheet: if cell A1 uses B1 and C1, it doesn't matter whether B1 or C1 is calculated first — A1 will get the same answer either way. The formal proof uses a diamond property: if you can reach state S by evaluating cell X first then cell Y, or by evaluating Y first then X, both paths arrive at the same state S. This matters because it means Cell programs can be parallelized safely — multiple LLMs could evaluate different cells simultaneously and the result is guaranteed correct. It also means debugging is easier: you never have to worry about race conditions or ordering bugs.\n\nWhat does 'directed acyclic graph (DAG)' mean?\nA directed acyclic graph is like a family tree where arrows only point forward in time — from grandparents to parents to children, never backwards. 'Directed' means the arrows have a direction (parent points to child, not the other way). 'Acyclic' means there are no loops — you can't follow the arrows and end up back where you started, just like you can't be your own grandparent. In Cell, each task points to the tasks it depends on, forming this kind of one-way tree.\n\nWhat does 'diamond property' mean?\nImagine you're making a sandwich and you need to add both lettuce and tomato. The diamond property says it doesn't matter whether you put the lettuce on first and then the tomato, or the tomato first and then the lettuce — you end up with the same sandwich either way. It's called 'diamond' because if you draw the two possible orders on paper, the paths split apart and then meet back up, making a diamond shape.\n\nWhat does 'immutable' mean?\nImmutable means something that can never be changed once it's finished — like writing in permanent marker instead of pencil. Once you write an answer in permanent marker, nobody can erase it or change it. In Cell, once a calculation produces its answer, that answer is locked forever."

  yield remaining-hard ≡ []

  yield leaf-score ≡ 10

-- oracle checks:
