⊢ format-output
  given collect-explanations→full-explanation ≡ "Confluence means that no matter what order you evaluate cells in a Cell program, you always get the same final result..."
  given concept→text ≡ "How does Cell's confluence property work and why does it matter?"
  yield final-explanation

  ∴ Format «collect-explanations→full-explanation» as a clean, readable document...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield final-explanation ≡ "How does Cell's confluence property work and why does it matter?\n\nConfluence means that no matter what order you evaluate cells in a Cell program, you always get the same final result. This works because Cell uses a directed acyclic graph — a structure like a family tree where arrows only point forward, never backwards — and each cell declares exactly what inputs it needs. A cell only runs when all its inputs are frozen: finalized and permanently locked, like writing in permanent marker. Since frozen values can never change, two independent cells can be evaluated in either order without affecting each other. The formal proof uses what mathematicians call the diamond property — like making a sandwich where it doesn't matter whether you add the lettuce or tomato first, you get the same sandwich.\n\nThis matters because it means Cell programs can be safely parallelized: multiple LLMs can evaluate different cells at the same time, and the result is guaranteed correct. It also means debugging is simpler — you never need to worry about ordering bugs or things changing out from under you.\n\nDigging deeper: Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG)\nA DAG is like a family tree. 'Directed' means the arrows have a direction — parent points to child, not the reverse. 'Acyclic' means there are no loops — you can't follow the arrows and end up back where you started, just like you can't be your own grandparent. In Cell, each task points to the tasks it depends on, forming this kind of one-way tree so the computer always knows what to calculate first.\n\nDigging deeper: The Diamond Property\nImagine you need to put both lettuce and tomato on a sandwich. It doesn't matter which goes on first — you end up with the same sandwich. If you drew the two possible orders on paper, the paths would split apart and meet back up in a diamond shape. That's the diamond property: two different paths always reach the same destination.\n\nDigging deeper: Immutability\nImmutable means 'can never be changed.' Think of it like writing in permanent marker instead of pencil — once an answer is written, nobody can erase or alter it. In Cell, once a calculation produces its result, that result is locked forever. This is what makes the whole system trustworthy: every answer stays exactly as it was when other parts of the program relied on it.\n\nIn one sentence a 10-year-old could repeat: No matter what order a Cell program does its work, the answer is always the same — like how a sandwich tastes the same whether you add the lettuce or the tomato first."

-- oracle checks:
