-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 9 (0-8)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 1 (converged immediately when leaf-score = 10 ≥ 9)
-- ⊢∘ max was 3, used 1 — all sub-explanations terminated at depth 1
-- ⊢⊢ spawned: 3 explainer cells (explainer-0, explainer-1, explainer-2)
-- ⊢⊢ accumulate mode: would persist cells across iterations (only 1 iteration needed)
-- Guard clause fired: deepen skipped (remaining-hard was empty)
-- File-scope ⊨? active but never triggered (no oracle failures)
-- Cells evaluated: concept, explain, assess-comprehension, spawn-explainers,
--   explainer-0, explainer-1, explainer-2, collect-explanations, format-output
-- Cells skipped: deepen (guard clause → ⊥)
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: recursive termination via semantic judgment
--   The still-hard flag is a semantic judgment: each sub-explainer cell
--   decides whether its own explanation introduces new hard terms. All three
--   explainers judged still-hard = false, so the tree terminated at depth 1.
--   This is genuine recursive termination by semantic oracle — no structural
--   depth limit was needed (max 3 was headroom, not the binding constraint).
--   The comprehension oracle IS the halting condition.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: spawner accumulate mode is correct for explanation trees
--   Explanation trees should grow monotonically: once you've explained "DAG"
--   with a family tree analogy, that explanation should persist even if the
--   main explanation is revised in a subsequent ⊢∘ iteration. Using `replace`
--   would discard good sub-explanations. This is the inverse of the research
--   program (01) which uses `replace` because old experiment results become
--   stale when hypotheses change. The accumulate/replace distinction captures
--   a real semantic difference in how spawned cells relate to their parent loop.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: guard clause prevents wasted LLM calls
--   The deepen cell has a guard: `where len(remaining-hard) > 0`. When all
--   sub-explanations terminate (still-hard = false), remaining-hard is empty
--   and deepen is skipped entirely. Without the guard (v0.1 behavior), deepen
--   would execute with an empty list and produce a vacuous "no terms to deepen"
--   output — wasting an LLM call. The v0.2 guard clause saves one LLM
--   invocation per successful iteration. At scale, this compounds.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: wildcard deps enable clean spawner-to-collector flow
--   collect-explanations uses `given explainer-*→explanation` to gather all
--   sub-explanations without knowing how many spawner fired. This is the
--   canonical wildcard pattern: spawner creates N cells, collector gathers
--   all N outputs. Under accumulate mode with multiple ⊢∘ iterations, the
--   wildcard would re-resolve to include cells from ALL iterations — the
--   explanation tree grows but old branches are never pruned.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: aspirational oracles provide meaningful feedback
--   The oracles on explain ("explanation is 3-8 sentences", "addresses both
--   how and why") are aspirational under ⊢∘ but still serve a purpose: if
--   the first iteration's explanation were too short or one-sided, the oracle
--   failure messages would feed into the next iteration's prompt context via
--   the ⊨? retry mechanism. The oracles describe the TARGET quality — the
--   ⊢∘ loop's `until` condition gates convergence, but the oracles shape
--   the direction of improvement. In this trace, all aspirational oracles
--   passed on the first iteration, so no retry was needed.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 6: single-iteration convergence reveals concept difficulty
--   This concept ("confluence") converged in 1 iteration because all three
--   hard terms (DAG, diamond property, immutable) have clean everyday
--   analogies. A harder concept — say, "monadic composition" — would likely
--   produce sub-explanations with still-hard = true (e.g., "functor" or
--   "type constructor"), triggering iteration 2 with additional spawned
--   explainer cells. The program's structure gracefully handles both cases:
--   easy concepts converge fast, hard concepts recurse deeper, and the
--   comprehension oracle adapts the depth to the actual difficulty.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 7: ⊥ propagation from guard-skipped cells is clean
--   When deepen is skipped (guard false), its yields become ⊥. No downstream
--   cell depends on deepen's output — format-output takes from
--   collect-explanations, not deepen. This means the ⊥ is produced but never
--   consumed, which is the ideal case: the guard prevents unnecessary work
--   AND the dataflow graph routes around the skipped cell naturally. If a
--   future version added a cell depending on deepen→deeper-explanations,
--   it would need `given?` to tolerate the ⊥ case.
